<p><b>Geodesy</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/dʒiːˈɒd<s>ɪ</s>si/</a></span><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>), also called <b>geodetics</b>, a branch of <a href="/wiki/Earth_sciences" title="Earth sciences" class="mw-redirect">earth sciences</a>, is the scientific discipline that deals with the measurement and representation of the <a href="/wiki/Earth" title="Earth">Earth</a>, including its <a href="/wiki/Gravitational_field" title="Gravitational field">gravitational field</a>, in a three-dimensional time-varying space. Geodesists also study <a href="/wiki/Geodynamics" title="Geodynamics">geodynamical</a> phenomena such as <a href="/wiki/Crust_(geology)" title="Crust (geology)">crustal</a> motion, <a href="/wiki/Tide" title="Tide">tides</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Polar_motion" title="Polar motion">polar motion</a>. For this they design global and national <a href="/wiki/Control_network" title="Control network">control networks</a>, using <a href="/wiki/Space_techniques" title="Space techniques">space</a> and terrestrial techniques while relying on <a href="/wiki/Datum_(geodesy)" title="Datum (geodesy)">datums</a> and <a href="/wiki/Coordinate_system" title="Coordinate system">coordinate systems</a>.</p>
